1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:26,341
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:27,233 --> 00:00:31,841
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:35,829 --> 00:00:48,094
So I think if you were to choose one word which encapsulates the teaching of the Buddha when it comes to the practice as opposed to the theory, it would have to be this word Sati.

4
00:00:49,406 --> 00:01:19,296
s-a-t-i and its root in the Sanskrit means actual remembrance and it's used in that sort of way with certain exercises so we talk about buddha anusati recollection of the buddha recollection of the qualities of the buddha qualities of the dharma things like that even this methodism anusati but when it comes to the word sati the buddha is using it in a specific way

5
00:01:20,474 --> 00:01:26,045
And with it he always puts these words, ariya, which we translate as noble.

6
00:01:31,215 --> 00:01:38,769
It's probably more right to say sort of correct or that sort of awareness that leads to liberation.

7
00:01:39,171 --> 00:01:40,373
And that's what he's really saying.

8
00:01:45,787 --> 00:01:51,120
And from his life story he sort of happens upon it.

9
00:01:53,789 --> 00:02:01,028
The teaching of the time tended to be about developing mental states that we now call the absorptions or jhanas.

10
00:02:03,049 --> 00:02:20,150
And although they're very blissful states, and you find them in all religions, because it's brought about by contemplations, this metta practice that we're doing, if you do it very strongly, it will create the bliss within inside you.

11
00:02:20,169 --> 00:02:30,542
But they also suffer from impermanence, so it didn't actually produce the answer he was looking for, about human suffering.

12
00:02:30,926 --> 00:02:34,731
It still presented him with his existential angst.

13
00:02:38,135 --> 00:02:43,824
And then he tried the self-mortification, if you remember, which is really the understanding that the body's at fault.

14
00:02:45,906 --> 00:02:48,909
And our appetites and greeds come from the body, you see.

15
00:02:49,850 --> 00:02:55,859
And therefore you have to, as it were, renounce the body to an extent that you almost kill it.

16
00:02:56,019 --> 00:02:57,441
I mean, he got very thinned.

17
00:02:59,935 --> 00:03:01,896
And that didn't take him anywhere.

18
00:03:03,858 --> 00:03:14,227
It was only when he had been revived by that palatia rice pudding that he has this memory of childhood, you see.

19
00:03:16,508 --> 00:03:18,830
And he's watching his father doing the prying ceremony.

20
00:03:20,271 --> 00:03:24,134
And in the scriptures it talks about the first absorption.

21
00:03:25,537 --> 00:03:29,520
But there's something else in that absorption which wasn't there before him.

22
00:03:31,103 --> 00:03:33,846
And we call them vipassana absorptions.

23
00:03:35,489 --> 00:03:44,360
And that quality that was there, that wasn't in the practice that he'd been doing with these other teachers, was the intelligence.

24
00:03:44,379 --> 00:03:51,127
So he's watching his father, absorbed in watching his father, but with that question mark in the mind.

25
00:03:53,471 --> 00:03:59,018
And that's why I have that picture of the back given to me by an Irish student.

26
00:03:59,038 --> 00:04:00,520
The little girl is reaching out.

27
00:04:01,495 --> 00:04:30,591
and pulling away a leaf to discover this beautiful butterfly but you can see that she's coming from the position of don't know and it's quite frightening for her so when we open up to ourselves like this it can be a bit frightening but what's the power behind it is this intelligence and this intelligence, this knowing is that within us which is to be liberated

28
00:04:31,499 --> 00:04:33,862
Because the problem lies within the knowing itself.

29
00:04:35,064 --> 00:04:43,074
The knowing doesn't know where it's at and it makes a wrong decision, it makes a wrong association.

30
00:04:45,718 --> 00:04:51,567
And if I were to choose one word for this sati, which is often translated as awareness, mindfulness and all that,

31
00:04:52,237 --> 00:04:54,923
For me, the word that really encapsulates it is knowing.

32
00:04:56,365 --> 00:05:04,379
And we're rather lucky in English that we have this gerund, which is a verbal noun.

33
00:05:05,362 --> 00:05:08,247
And in so doing, it doesn't coagulate into a thing.

34
00:05:08,668 --> 00:05:09,548
It's not the known.

35
00:05:09,730 --> 00:05:10,992
It's not our knowing.

36
00:05:12,535 --> 00:05:15,360
So you take away its personality, its

37
00:05:15,560 --> 00:05:24,074
It's solidity, it's just knowing, just like being, becoming, you see.

38
00:05:24,093 --> 00:05:35,711
And that quality of just knowing what is happening liberates the knowing from a delusion.

39
00:05:36,956 --> 00:05:42,846
And that intelligence, that internal intelligence we have, which is part of sati, the awareness.

40
00:05:43,026 --> 00:05:48,113
The awareness really is pointing to just that openness, the receptivity that you need.

41
00:05:51,619 --> 00:05:57,327
And that knowing is beyond our control.

42
00:05:57,387 --> 00:06:03,437
When insights come, even in ordinary daily life, it's not as though that we've thought them through.

43
00:06:03,838 --> 00:06:09,708
Sometimes you go to bed with a problem and you wake up and it's like it's as clear as day.

44
00:06:10,790 --> 00:06:12,492
And you haven't thought about it.

45
00:06:13,975 --> 00:06:19,944
So there's something about this intelligence within us which doesn't belong to the thinking mind.

46
00:06:20,444 --> 00:06:25,533
And that's why in the meditation we make such an effort to close the thinking mind.

47
00:06:26,213 --> 00:06:28,598
In so doing we liberate this intelligence.

48
00:06:29,658 --> 00:06:57,927
and the awareness is the passive side of this intelligence it's the openness it's the receptivity and as we receive information there sparks forward out of it this grasping this sudden understanding and that's really the panya part this wisdom part within us so sati as you might say your default position you see

49
00:06:58,108 --> 00:07:02,634
And in our standing meditation, see, just to come back to that bare awareness.

50
00:07:06,461 --> 00:07:07,661
Lovely word is stop.

51
00:07:09,345 --> 00:07:11,747
Just to catch the moment after you say stop.

52
00:07:13,651 --> 00:07:15,954
Before the mind rushes in for the next thing to do.

53
00:07:15,994 --> 00:07:25,007
It's just catching that moment and recognizing that in that moment there's this tremendous potential because you're open to what there is.

54
00:07:26,668 --> 00:07:26,749
See?

55
00:07:27,757 --> 00:07:38,930
So developing that awareness in his sitting, you see, he was then able to let the heart and mind, all the conditioning that he had, just express itself.

56
00:07:40,110 --> 00:07:47,678
And it was in that that he became aware of how we manufacture the world, where the actual original delusion lies.

57
00:07:48,901 --> 00:07:52,064
And it lies in the belief that we're human beings.

58
00:07:53,185 --> 00:07:53,605
Very simple.

59
00:07:55,166 --> 00:07:57,629
That we are this psychophysical organism.

60
00:07:59,045 --> 00:08:13,000
And once we've made that delusive step, we're driven to make the best we can of this world, to seek happiness in sensual pleasure, in what the world can give us.

61
00:08:13,021 --> 00:08:26,757
And it's not as though the world doesn't give us happiness or joy, but it can never totally satisfy this search, because the search is for something eternal, not dying, the immortal, the deathless, as he would put it.

62
00:08:27,648 --> 00:08:33,534
So trying to find that deathless dharma, the amatadhamma, you see.

63
00:08:34,697 --> 00:08:40,724
We say it when we repeat these phrases, the unborn, the undying, the uncreated, the unconditioned.

64
00:08:41,605 --> 00:08:42,566
What is that, you see?

65
00:08:43,086 --> 00:08:46,071
Where do we find that position?

66
00:08:46,471 --> 00:08:50,996
Within the world of creation, within the world of transient things.

67
00:08:52,558 --> 00:08:55,241
So that's the process of vipassana.

68
00:08:55,863 --> 00:09:14,277
Every time we make something an object within us, be it a thought, an emotion, a feeling, a sensation, in order to do that we've stepped out of creation, we've stepped out of the condition and we're discovering this place within us which is the non-condition.

69
00:09:15,876 --> 00:09:24,663
And in so doing, we're discovering the real, true, deeper meaning of samasati, this noble awareness.

70
00:09:25,785 --> 00:09:30,460
And that's our Buddha nature.

71
00:09:32,717 --> 00:09:41,246
And then once we become certain about that, once we begin to understand that, then the training begins.

72
00:09:43,408 --> 00:09:47,472
Because we're constantly drawn back into the old conditioning.

73
00:09:47,493 --> 00:09:48,674
And that's the problem.

74
00:09:48,955 --> 00:09:50,255
The old conditioning is heavy.

75
00:09:51,357 --> 00:09:52,839
It'll keep sucking us back in.

76
00:09:53,879 --> 00:10:01,408
But every time we come back to that position of just awareness, bare attentiveness, pure knowing,

77
00:10:01,674 --> 00:10:08,606
we keep reinforcing within ourselves where the object of our quest lies.

78
00:10:11,130 --> 00:10:20,847
So that's why this practice of vipassana is fundamental to the spiritual life really, because it's so easy to get lost in daily life.

79
00:10:21,267 --> 00:10:32,039
But just to settle in the morning, a little bit in the evening, and as many small times as we can during the day, to re-establish just that position of pure knowing.

80
00:10:32,059 --> 00:10:34,562
Just coming back down into that default position.

81
00:10:34,663 --> 00:10:36,524
So we did it in the standing meditation.

82
00:10:36,845 --> 00:10:42,552
See, just to stop.

83
00:10:42,572 --> 00:10:43,613
And then you act.

84
00:10:45,027 --> 00:11:07,288
next thing to be done and it's that practice of constantly stopping and coming back down to that pure awareness which is the practice I can only hope my words have been of some assistance may you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later

